Here are both approaches for MAUI Shell navigation with `IQueryAttributable`.

**1. Register the route:**
```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
Routing.RegisterRoute("productdetails", typeof(ProductDetailsPage));
```

**2. Navigate from ProductListPage (both approaches):**
```csharp
// Simple string parameter
async void OnProductTapped(Product product)
{
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"productdetails?id={product.Id}");
}

// Passing the full object
async void OnProductTapped(Product product)
{
    var navParams = new Dictionary<string, object>
    {
        { "product", product }
    };
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("productdetails", navParams);
}
```

**3. Receive data via `IQueryAttributable` on the ViewModel:**
```csharp
public class ProductDetailsViewModel : ObservableObject, IQueryAttributable
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    private string _productId;

    [ObservableProperty]
    private Product _product;

    public void ApplyQueryAttributes(IDictionary<string, object> query)
    {
        // Approach 1: simple string
        if (query.TryGetValue("id", out var id))
            ProductId = id.ToString();

        // Approach 2: full object
        if (query.TryGetValue("product", out var obj) && obj is Product p)
            Product = p;
    }
}
```

**4. Wire up the target page:**
```csharp
// ProductDetailsPage.xaml.cs
public ProductDetailsPage(ProductDetailsViewModel vm)
{
    InitializeComponent();
    BindingContext = vm;
}
```

**Key differences:**

| | String query param | `Dictionary<string, object>` |
|---|---|---|
| **Syntax** | interpolated URI | overload with `IDictionary` |
| **Types** | strings only | any object |
| **Deep-link safe** | ✅ yes | ❌ no (object isn't serializable to URI) |

Use the string approach for bookmarkable/deep-linkable routes; use the dictionary approach when you already have the object in memory and want to avoid a redundant fetch.
